segments.text: As a result of the financial strength of the developers' financial support, which was Gibraltar Savings, which is the largest savings and loan in Texas, at that time had assets of over $8 billion, they were able to master plan the entire development and put in all of the major infrastructure in phase one.
So what was proposed was a new community of some 65,000 to 80,000 people
that would be within the jurisdiction of McKinney, which is a town of 18,000 people, which, believe it or not, has more historical structures than the city of Galveston.
Is that right?
It's a quaint, fascinating little town that has some very progressive staff that has the character of some wonderful 19th century architecture in urban form.
Where is it located?
It's straight north of Dallas on Nile.
Highway, past Plain 75.
Yes, just north of Plain.
So I was hired in association with a financial consultant to organize and lead a negotiation team that would negotiate the approvals of these development proposals.
It was envisioned that this development would have, as I said, 65,000 to 80,000 people, three 18-hole golf courses, seven lakes, nine schools,

hundreds of miles of streets, three fire stations, perhaps a new city hall, and a sports board of other community facilities and infrastructure improvements that would be required for that development.
As a result of

Again, the experience of infrastructure planning and the financing requirements on the one hand, and knowing a bit about the role of city planning and growth management, and having a little experience in negotiation, we were able to negotiate what I believe was the largest development agreement in the history of Texas.
And in a matter of 90 days...
Larger than what role?
Well, the Woodlands was not a development agreement.
It was just a development.
But this was a negotiated agreement, an actual contractual agreement between the city of McKinney and the developers of Flying M Ranch in Gibraltar City.
Contractual agreement that required a series of quid pro quos.
The city would provide, would annex and provide certain zoning.
And the developer would install certain infrastructure.

and other community services in a whole medley of amenity packages, if you will, that would allow the city to, as it quadrupled in size, to maintain a quality of urban services and quality of urban form that would be commensurate with what the city had before.
It was on the order of magnitude of
eighty odd million dollars worth of improvements that were negotiated and agreed upon.
And it involved numerous firms working for the city as well as for the developer to bring all this together.
But it was, I think, to be a very profitable project for the developer to have all this comprehensively planned.
And for the city it was
the benefit of comprehensive planning on a scale that most cities never had the opportunity to do, let alone sign on the bottom line.
What has been their experience since signing?
I have not been able to monitor it because I quickly got involved in some other
water-related projects.

But I think those three examples represent this whole new dimension of planning that we coined as negotiated growth management, which involves a lot of the experiences that people talk about today in terms of mediation and dispute resolution, negotiation,
getting to yes, as one book calls it, and the basic physical planning and financial planning dimensions that I think urban planners need to understand anyway.
I keep asking myself, but isn't this what has always happened?
And aren't we just using new buzzwords for something that has always been processed?
And I don't know what the answer to that nagging question is.
I know that MIT and Harvard and the joint program up there are heavily involved in negotiation.
And certainly, I think that planning education, getting back to that a minute,

has always been somewhat neglectful of the role of relating the planning process to the decision process in a way that makes it clear to students how they must react and respond to decision makers and those that they deal with.

I think that's one of the weak points of the A&M program, with the exception of people like Jim Gardner, who has always been in it and has run for city council successfully several times, and can speak with total authority on that subject.
But I personally have
I asked the question when I've seen some of the new articles coming out on the subject of negotiation and conferences being held on negotiation and so forth.
What's new about it?

Well, I didn't mean to say that what I was doing was innovative, but I think the nuance that has really become a standard operating procedure only in the last two or three years is what is often called development agreements.
These are negotiated agreements between the public and private sector.
They're not ventures.
to see what can be done by a civic-minded developer in an entrepreneurial-oriented city necessarily.

But it's what was normally a clash between the city struggling with how it can manage and sometimes control growth on one hand, and the developer that sees the regulatory milieu as a maze and a series of obstacles that
often require hiring lobbyists to overcome.
What has come out of the projects that I've been involved in is a negotiation process that is very legal in nature.
It comes out with contractual agreements based on hedging the risk for the entrepreneur and securing a lot of the
amenities that cities often never are able to get commitments for.
until the citizens are already there begging for it.
I'm also leery of too many lawyers meddling in planning, and I cite as an example the American Law Institute's Model Land Development Code, which would have

reduced the process that you're describing to simply written briefs, and everything would have had to be in writing, and everyone would have had to be committed to the gills before any contact was made.
Which is not financially feasible the way the banks operate.
It didn't leave much room for exactly what you're interested in, negotiation, because everybody's position would have been hardened before there had been any confrontation at all.
That's a good point.

And I feel that resolving it through discussion, negotiation, whatever you want to call it, exchange of ideas and trade-offs, is knowing what the position of the government agency is in terms of its goals and objectives and policies is certainly the way to go.
But case in point is an attorney would never fathom the idea that a contractual agreement
would have the ability to be evaluated and updated and monitored over time to allow appropriate revisions to be made at various milestones, which is really what planners always
require in order to keep something from getting so outmoded that you have to just throw the whole damn thing out.
And so in these negotiated agreements, those updates and abilities by mutual agreement to revise things and plan for that ahead of time was something that, again, attorneys
really had to struggle to find the boilerplate language to put it down.
That would have been amusing.

You may not, I don't think you agree with me on this, that the American, well the Model Land Development Code I think failed miserably in not requiring a plan diagram to be a part of an adopted comprehensive plan.
Well, I think plan diagrams are very important for a couple of reasons.
Anytime you're talking about land, real property, the ability to communicate that is essential in terms of people's ability to relate what they own to what the police powers are going to do.
be affecting what they own and what other people own.
And maps are communication devices.
Well, you know, the Austin Tomorrow Plan did not do this.
Well, they did it at such a gross and small scale that it had no import to the individual property owner.
That's all right, but I don't think that they did it really.
They had growth corridors established, which is quite a different matter.
And it didn't show a circulation system.
And it didn't show a lot of things that a plan diagram would show.
Nor did it deal adequately with the implementation strategies.
Very weak in implementation.

But I think the biggest failing of that plan, and it's true of a lot of other plans too, is that the commitment of subsequent city councils was not there to fund it through capital improvements program.
Without those bottom line dollars supporting those plans, there's no way for a developer to see the benefits of the city's ways.
Well, pressure started to build up regarding the plan and its perceived restrictive nature.
And that was apparently enough to kill it.
So they've started in with an entirely new planning program.
Ken, thanks very much for your time and your input to this program of the American Planning Association Texas Chapter.
This tape will be transcribed and God only knows when that will happen.
The right things are going at the moment, but eventually you'll get a transcription which I will
then look for you to make changes in.
Any additions or deletions that come to mind at that time would be gratefully appreciated.
And we'll then put it back onto the computer disk and run out our final hard copy.
Thanks again.
Thank you, Bob.
